BIRNIN KEBBI – The National president of National council of women societies NCWS Dr Gloria Laraba Shoda has called on Buhari led government to increase the number of women in the art of governance in Nigeria. Shoda made the call in Birnin Kebbi on Saturday during the affirmation of new executives of the National council Kebbi state chapter, according to her the number of women in government positions indicated that , the female gender are not adequately represented at the National level “I know mister president will say he gave us finance, humanitarian and women affairs that’s not enough considering our numbers and capabilities to lead in various capacities she said. She explained that, the percentage of women in governance is just about 6% while in other African nations like Uganda they have about 60% representations therefore ours is poor there is need to bring more women on board in order to fill the gender gab. PDP Victory In FCT Council Polls, Good Omen -Ayu How Witches Took Us To Court, Akwa Ibom Governor Recounts She added that,the National council expects Buhari to do that before he leaves office, she charged women to use their large numbers to contribute to peace building and progress of the country instead of using their large numbers to gossip, while urging women across the country to partake in politics she lauded women who made attempts to seek presidential seats and post in politics. Shortly after dissolving old excos of Kebbi council she administered the oath of office to 15 new executives who will stir the boat of the council for the period of five years in Kebbi state. In her welcome address, the outgoing Kebbi state president of NCWS Balkisu Atuna Danga thanked the National president for her motherly care and love and her contribution to the success of her tenure. She explained that as state president NCWS experienced territorial expansion as she took over with just 10 excos all dominant within the state capital but she is now handing over at least 150 executives which she painstakingly sourced from the four emirates in Kebbi state namely Gwandu, Argungu, Yauri and Zuru all in her quest to reposition the council in the state while wishing the incoming excos a resounding success she urged them to build on the existing structures in order to propel the council to greater heights.